    "body": "@davidkna thank you for the reply.\n\nthat was my first thought when I noticed the problem, so I tried just for testing something like:\n```toml\ncommands = [\n    [\"nu\", \"-c\", \"$nu.config-path\"]\n]\n```\n\nbut it didn't work. Despite to this, thanks a lot for the moving direction. \nI am able to get the correct output when I moved the `--version` into the same command as `rg` itself.\n\n```toml\ncommands = [\n  [ \"nu\",\n    \"-c\",\n    \"make -p | 'some rg seach' | do {^$in --version}\"\n  ],\n```\n\nprobably because the use of consecutive commands applies it sequentially, without waiting for the output of the previous one, so the command gave output in the form of a version of nushell itself like `v0.105.1`\n```toml\n[\"nu\", \"-c\". \"some rg search\", \"--version\" ]\n# -> v0.105.1\n```\nbut how? after all, `nu -c --version` should give `--version` string as output.\n\n",
